  "prompt": "Which problems should I attempt first on TopCoder?",
  "response": "When tackling problems on TopCoder, it's generally a good idea to approach them strategically to maximize efficiency and effectiveness. Here\u2019s a step-by-step guide to help you decide which problems to attempt first:\n\n1. **Assess the Difficulty Levels**\n   - **Div 1 vs. Div 2**: If you're in Division 2, start with the easier problems (250-point problems). If you're in Division 1, even the \"easier\" problems can be challenging, so gauge your skill level appropriately.\n   - **Point Values**: Typically, 250-point problems are the easiest, followed by 500-point, and then 1000-point problems. Start with lower-point problems.\n\n2. **Read All Problem Statements**\n   - Quickly skim through all problem statements to get a sense of what each one entails.\n   - Identify any problems that seem familiar or align with your strengths.\n\n3. **Prioritize Problems Based on Your Strengths**\n   - **Algorithm Types**: If you\u2019re strong in dynamic programming, greedy algorithms, graph theory, or any other area, prioritize problems that seem to fall into those categories.\n   - **Implementation Complexity**: Some problems may have straightforward logic but require careful implementation. If you\u2019re confident in your coding skills, these might be quick wins.\n\n4. **Time Management**\n   - **Start with the Easiest**: Begin with the problem you find easiest to ensure you secure some points early on.\n   - **Move to Medium Difficulty**: After solving the easiest problem, tackle the next one that you feel confident about.\n   - **Save the Hardest for Last**: If time permits, attempt the most challenging problem. Even a partial solution can earn you points.\n\n5. **Plan Your Approach**\n   - **Break Down the Problem**: For each problem, break it down into smaller subproblems or steps.\n   - **Estimate Time**: Estimate how long each problem will take and stick to your plan to avoid spending too much time on a single problem.\n\n6. **Handle Edge Cases**\n   - **Initial Thoughts**: Think about possible edge cases and test cases while planning your solution.\n   - **Implement and Test**: Write your solution and thoroughly test it against various cases to ensure correctness.\n\n7. **Review and Submit**\n   - **Code Review**: Review your code for any potential errors or optimizations.\n   - **Submit Confidently**: Once you\u2019re confident in your solution, submit it and move on to the next problem.\n\nBy following this structured approach, you can maximize your efficiency and effectiveness on TopCoder, ensuring that you tackle problems that align with your strengths and manage your time wisely. Good luck!",
